{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12455"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12455"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.51,0.23,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4963"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85925"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"595"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1352"},{"type":"tags","id":"1501"},{"type":"tags","id":"1837"},{"type":"tags","id":"2968"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painful swelling in her right breast that started as an area of redness five days ago. She is currently breastfeeding her three-month-old son. She has no significant medical history and the only medication she is currently taking is paracetamol as needed for the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her blood pressure is 112/76 mmHg, pulse rate 92/min, and temperature 39\u00b0C. Her right breast is tender and erythematous with a fluctuant swelling over the right upper quadrant. The skin overlying the swelling does not appear necrosed or thin. The left breast appears normal on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cool compress and paracetamol","Antibiotics and needle aspiration","Incision and drainage","Biopsy followed by antibiotics","Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug and encourage breastfeeding as normal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a tender, erythematous, and fluctuant swelling in the breast, together with fever, in the context of lactation. This is most consistent with a lactational abscess. The history describes progression from mastitis to abscess formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics and needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment. Antibiotic duration is commonly 10\u201314 days; however, a shorter course may be appropriate if there is rapid resolution of surrounding cellulitis. In addition, drainage of the abscess is essential to achieve source control. Needle aspiration with fluid culture and sensitivity is often recommended as the first-line intervention for lactational abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, patients most often require recurrent aspirations for definitive resolution. An alternative to be considered in these cases is drain placement at the time of the index procedure, especially for larger or persistent abscesses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter aspiration or drain placement, mothers should continue breastfeeding from the affected breast. Milk fistula rate is less than 2%, but lactation must be managed appropriately and hyperlactation treated if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for cases where there is marked skin thinning, ischaemia, or pressure necrosis, or if needle aspiration or drain placement is unsuccessful. In this case, the skin is not necrosed or thin, so less invasive management is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy followed by antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if there is suspicion of malignancy, such as a non-resolving mass or atypical features. However in this context, the clinical features are typical for abscess and immediate biopsy is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug and encourage breastfeeding as normal\u003C/strong\u003E is the cornerstone of conservative management for early mastitis. Most cases of lactational mastitis are not bacterial but rather inflammatory in origin, and antibiotics are not indicated in all cases. Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and cold compresses are effective in reducing inflammation and providing symptom relief. However, when a fluctuant swelling is present, indicating abscess formation, conservative management alone is insufficient and drainage is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECool compresses and paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some symptomatic relief but are not sufficient as definitive management for a breast abscess, which requires both antibiotics and drainage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Breast abscess in a lactating person requires both antibiotics and drainage, with needle aspiration as first-line intervention.","Repeated aspirations are often needed for definitive resolution of lactational mastitis with abscess formation, but drain placement may be considered for persistent or large abscesses.","Breastfeeding should continue from the affected breast after aspiration or drainage of a lactational mastitis-associated abscess."],"references":["Mitchell KB, Johnson HM, Rodr\u00edguez JM, Eglash A, Scherzinger C, Widmer K, Berens P, Miller B; Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine. Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine Clinical Protocol# 36: the mastitis spectrum, revised 2022. Breastfeed Med. 2022 May 1;17(5):360-76. Available from: https://www.bfmed.org/assets/ABM%20Protocol%20%2336.pdf","Boakes E, Woods A, Johnson N, Kadoglou N. Breast Infection: A Review of Diagnosis and Management Practices. Eur J Breast Health. 2018 Jul 1;14(3):136-143. doi: 10.5152/ejbh.2018.3871. PMID: 30123878; PMCID: PMC6092150. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30123878/","Kataria K, Srivastava A, Dhar A. Management of lactational mastitis and breast abscesses: review of current knowledge and practice. Indian J Surg. 2013 Dec;75(6):430-5. doi: 10.1007/s12262-012-0776-1. Epub 2012 Dec 12. PMID: 24465097; PMCID: PMC3900741. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24465097/","Ozseker B, Ozcan UA, Rasa K, Cizmeli OM. Treatment of breast abscesses with ultrasound-guided aspiration and irrigation in the emergency setting. Emerg Radiol. 2008 Mar;15(2):105-8. doi: 10.1007/s10140-007-0683-0. Epub 2008 Jan 10. PMID: 18193464. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18193464/","Dixon JM, Khan LR. Treatment of breast infection. BMJ. 2011 Feb 11;342:d396. doi: 10.1136/bmj.d396. PMID: 21317199. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21317199/","Irusen H, Rohwer AC, Steyn DW, Young T. Treatments for breast abscesses in breastfeeding women. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Aug 17;2015(8):CD010490. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD010490.pub2. PMID: 26279276; PMCID: PMC9226721. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26279276/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85925"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12455"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85925"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T09:42:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T09:43:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou